## How Playback Is Selected

xg2g uses a backend-driven playback decision model. Depending on source truth,
client capabilities, and operator policy, a session can take one of four paths:

| Path | When xg2g uses it | Typical output |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **DirectPlay** | Client can consume the selected output as-is | `direct_mp4` / direct file playback |
| **DirectStream** | Codecs are compatible but delivery needs a container/protocol bridge | HLS without full re-encode |
| **Transcode** | Codec, container, or client constraints require repair | Browser-safe HLS |
| **Deny** | No safe compatible path is available | Fail-closed error response |

## Default `universal` Delivery Policy

`streaming.delivery_policy=universal` is the current supported policy value.
When xg2g needs a broad browser-compatibility path, it targets this default
transcode/remux output:

| Component | Specification |
| :--- | :--- |
| **Video** | H.264 (AVC) |
| **Audio** | AAC |
| **Container** | fMP4 (Fragmented MP4) |
| **Protocol** | HLS |

This is the default compatibility target, not the only playback outcome.
DirectPlay and DirectStream remain valid outputs when the decision engine says
they are safe, including HEVC and AV1 when the client advertises support.

Tier-1 aligned with Apple HLS guidance for the compatibility path.

**Non-Goals**

- ❌ HEVC or AV1 as the default fallback encode target (compatibility first)
- ❌ UI transcoding controls (fixed server policy)
- ❌ Browser workarounds (Safari is the reference)
- ❌ Forcing every session through HLS remux/transcode when a direct path is valid

